☠️3 years ago today I explanted my 6 year old breast implants☠️ 

💧In 2012, I decided to put in 375cc breast implants. At the time I wanted a more feminine look, as I am athletic and muscular. I thought that this is what I needed. 🙄 I loved them at first, but after a while they became uncomfortable. I started to feel inflamed along with other symptoms.

💧Over the last couple years of having them I started to notice one was changing shape and seemingly getting smaller. I am known to be a hypochondriac so of course this was brushed off. But over the course of a year or so I really couldn’t shake the feeling of something being off with them. I started to think that one was ruptured. As I started to make the leap into inquiring about removal, I saw a couple doctors. I voiced my concern of a possible rupture every single doctor told me there’s no way I had a rupture and the chances of a rupture is extremely slim. I chose a surgeon and the first thing I was told as I woke up from surgery was that I was right and the one was ruptured! It was a literal pile of mush inside my body. Breast implants contain some heavy metals and a bunch of nasty ingredients. I was so relieved that they were out! 

💧Unfortunately I developed a complication from the surgery. And three days later my one breast filled with blood and I had internal bleeding. I rushed to the hospital and over the course of a couple hours my one boob tripled in size, filling with blood (was told later it was 700cc of blood) and the pain excruciating. I was told as I went into emergency surgery that I might need a blood transfusion. I am so grateful I woke from that surgery without a transfusion. 

💧No judgement if you have them. But lessened learn- do research and make informed medical decisions when looking to put a foreign object inside your body. Be your own health advocate, only you know your own body.
📷 @kai.york.official

I was chatting the other day with a friend, joking about how much time I used to have for working out when I was a trainer at David Barton. 

Those days we would just train and hang out with each other on the gym floor for hours. 

Now days my fitness is totally different. I’m running an online coaching and personal training business, running RE biz, and being a mom and home caretaker. Some days I get help, but the majority I don’t. 

I have many hats that I juggle and now days my workouts are so much shorter and effective than my gymrat days. My training is a lot of the same exercises day in and out.. nothing fancy. But I put in the consistency and the effort. 

If you’re unsure of where to start reach out! Let me help you build a program based off of YOUR goals👊🏼👊🏼

It’s finally feeling like fall here in Texas! Is there not a better way for fall feels to celebrate with a batch of healthy pumpkin bread!? I think not 💁🏻‍♀️

BREAD:

1/4 cup butter melted
1 1/2 tsp of vanilla extract
2 eggs
1/3 cup brown sugar
1/4 cup of monk fruit sweetener (or sweetener of choice)
1 15 oz can pumpkin purée
1 1/2 cup gluten free flour
1/4 cup of Level 1 Protein powder vanilla
1 1/2 tsp baking soda
1 1/2 tsp baking powder
1/4 tsp salt
2 tsp cinnamon
1 tsp nutmeg
1/2 tsp ground cloves
Optional: add in 1/4 cup walnuts

FROSTING:

8 oz of cream cheese (I use Neufchâtel)
1 scoop of Level 1 protein powder vanilla
1/2 tsp vanilla
Dashes of milk

Melt butter and mix in wet ingredients.
Add in dry ingredients. 
Grease a loaf pan

Bake at 350 for 50 mins

Chocolate PB Protein Cups!

This recipe is pretty easy and can be stored in the freezer for a a future tasty treat! 

PB Base

3/4 cup Almond flour
1 cup of Peanut butter
2 tbsp Honey
1/2 scoop 1st phorm Salted PB protein powder (link in bio)
1 scoop unflavored 1st Phorm collagen (link in bio)

Chocolate Top

1 cup of chocolate chips
Dollop of coconut oil 
(Melt in microwave stirring every 20 sec)

Mix all PB base ingredients together and roll 2” balls. 
Forming the balls as crust in the mini silicone cup pan. 
Drizzle melted chocolate on top. 
Pop in the freezer for 15 mins 
Recipe makes 3 dozen
